    <section class="band" id="stan4j-alternative">
      <div class="container compare-split">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Stan4J alternative</p>
          <h2>Coming from Stan4J</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-copy">
          <p>Stan4J solved a real problem: local Java structure analysis that made dependencies, cycles, tangles, and metrics visible. It's no longer a practical option. The product disappeared years ago, can't be bought or downloaded through any current path, and its old Java support ceiling is mostly academic now that the tool is gone.</p>
          <p>AtlasArc doesn't try to recreate Stan4J screen by screen. It brings the useful part back to current IntelliJ projects: direct structural visibility, interactive package exploration, cycle diagnosis, architecture metrics, and a route from any finding back to source.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="structure101-replacement">
      <div class="container compare-split">
        <div>
          <p class="eyebrow">Structure101 replacement</p>
          <h2>Coming from Structure101</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-copy">
          <p>Structure101 was a serious architecture product: LSM exploration, dependency matrices, authored structure specs, build checks, reports, and snapshot workflows. It's also no longer sold, which leaves a real gap for teams that still need to inspect, explain, and govern architecture inside current codebases.</p>
          <p>AtlasArc covers the daily work former users miss: graph and matrix navigation, subject and boundary reads, cycle triage, source-level exception governance, hotspot prioritization, and Architecture Audit Reports. It should not be read as a full clone of every historical Structure101 workflow.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band" id="codemr-sonar">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Adjacent</span>
          <h2>CodeMR and Sonar are different comparisons</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-fit-grid compare-fit-grid--two">
          <article class="compare-fit">
            <h3>CodeMR is not the benchmark for interaction</h3>
            <p>CodeMR is best read as a metrics-oriented inspection plugin. AtlasArc is built around interactive architecture work: moving from topology to matrix to hotspots, pinning subjects, tracing cycle evidence, and producing reports that explain architectural findings.</p>
          </article>
          <article class="compare-fit">
            <h3>Sonar is a complement, not a target</h3>
            <p>Sonar is the broad static-analysis and security governance platform. AtlasArc is the local IntelliJ architecture workbench you use when you need to understand, explain, and act on the structure behind those risks.</p>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band band-alt" id="typescript-and-enforcement">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Companions</span>
          <h2>TypeScript artifacts and CI enforcement</h2>
        </div>
        <div class="compare-fit-grid compare-fit-grid--two">
          <article class="compare-fit">
            <h3>From dependency-cruiser artifacts to exploration</h3>
            <p>For TypeScript, AtlasArc reads dependency-cruiser JSON generated by your project. It turns that static artifact into a navigable architecture model; it doesn't replace dependency-cruiser's parser, rules, or CI use.</p>
            <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/languages/typescript">TypeScript support &rarr;</a>
          </article>
          <article class="compare-fit">
            <h3>Evaluate AtlasArc governance in CI</h3>
            <p>The standalone evaluator reads the same committed governance file for Java, Kotlin, and TypeScript. JVM teams can also use AtlasArc's ArchUnit/JUnit adapter: accepted cycles pass the architecture test, while new ungoverned cycles still fail.</p>
            <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/docs/atlasarc-ci">AtlasArc CI guide &rarr;</a>
            <a class="btn btn-ghost" href="/docs/recipe-archunit-build">ArchUnit recipe &rarr;</a>
          </article>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="band">
      <div class="container">
        <div class="section-header">
          <span class="section-number">Limits</span>
          <h2>What AtlasArc does not claim</h2>
        </div>
        <ul class="compare-limits">
          <li>AtlasArc does not replace SonarQube's broad static-analysis, security, PR, and organization-wide governance platform.</li>
          <li>AtlasArc does not claim full historical Structure101 suite parity for authored specs, repository snapshots, and build products.</li>
          <li>AtlasArc does not replace IntelliJ IDEA's dependency analyzer, module diagrams, DSM, or source-navigation strengths.</li>
          <li>AtlasArc does not parse TypeScript semantically; it reads dependency-cruiser artifacts generated by your project.</li>
          <li>AtlasArc's class/file internals are a Topology detail layer, not a sixth lens or a new architecture-unit model.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </section>

